  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "What are some of the best books on investment?",
  "response": "There are many excellent books on investment that cater to various levels of expertise and investment philosophies. Here\u2019s a list of some of the most recommended ones, covering a range of topics from fundamental analysis to behavioral finance:\n\n1. **\"The Intelligent Investor\" by Benjamin Graham** - Often regarded as the bible of investing, this book emphasizes value investing and is known for its focus on long-term strategies.\n\n2. **\"A Random Walk Down Wall Street\" by Burton G. Malkiel** - This book presents various investment strategies and provides insight into the performance of different asset classes.\n\n3. **\"Common Stocks and Uncommon Profits\" by Philip A. Fisher** - Fisher shares his investment philosophy and provides insights into what to look for when evaluating a company\u2019s potential.\n\n4. **\"Security Analysis\" by Benjamin Graham and David Dodd** - A comprehensive guide that dives deep into the methods of evaluating stocks and bonds for investment.\n\n5. **\"The Little Book of Common Sense Investing\" by John C. Bogle** - The founder of Vanguard Group, Bogle makes a strong case for low-cost index fund investing.\n\n6. **\"One Up On Wall Street\" by Peter Lynch** - Lynch shares his experience managing the Fidelity Magellan Fund and provides insights on how individual investors can find winning stocks.\n\n7. **\"The Psychology of Investing\" by John R. Nofsinger** - This book explores the psychological aspects of investing and how emotions can impact decision-making.\n\n8. **\"Thinking, Fast and Slow\" by Daniel Kahneman** - While not exclusively an investment book, it provides valuable insights into human behavior and decision-making, which are crucial in investing.\n\n9. **\"Market Wizards\" by Jack D. Schwager** - This series of interviews with top traders provides diverse perspectives on trading strategies and philosophies.\n\n10. **\"The Most Important Thing\" by Howard Marks** - Marks shares his insights on risk assessment and market cycles from his perspective as a successful investor.\n\n11. **\"Rich Dad Poor Dad\" by Robert Kiyosaki** - While not a traditional investment book, it focuses on financial education and changing the way people think about money and investing.\n\n12. **\"The Dhandho Investor\" by Mohnish Pabrai** - A blend of value investing principles with a focus on low-risk, high-return investments.\n\nThese books cover a range of perspectives and philosophies about investing, and they are useful for both novice and experienced investors looking to deepen their understanding of the markets.",
